# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: amylose
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:amylose/acarbose] Acarbose is a starch blocker that works by inhibiting alpha glucosidase, an intestinal enzyme that releases glucose from larger carbohydrates such as starch and sucrose.
[src:amylose/acarbose] It is composed of an acarviosin moiety with a maltose at the reducing terminus.
[src:amylose/acarbose] Acarbose is inexpensive and popular in China, but not in the U.S.
[src:amylose/acarbose] One physician explains that U.S. use is limited, because it is not potent enough to offset side effects of diarrhea and flatulence.
[src:amylose/acarbose] In type II diabetic patients, acarbose averages an absolute decrease of 0.8 percentage points in HbA1c, which is a decrease of about 10% in typical HbA1c values in diabetes studies.
[src:amylose/acarbose] Individuals with higher baseline levels show higher reductions, about an 0.12% additional decrease for each point of baseline HbA1c.
[src:amylose/acarbose] Its effect on postprandial glucose, but not on HbA1c, scales with dose.
[src:amylose/acarbose] Among diabetic patients, acarbose may help reduce the damage done to blood vessels and kidneys by reducing glucose levels.
[src:amylose/acarbose] A Cochrane systematic review assessed the effect of alpha-glucosidase inhibitors in people with prediabetes, defined as impaired glucose tolerance, impaired fasting blood glucose, elevated glycated hemoglobin A1c (HbA1c).
[src:amylose/acarbose] Several studies showed that glucosidase inhibitors and alpha-amylase inhibitors promote loss of visceral fat and waist by acting as calorie restriction mimetics (linked to their acarbose-like action).
[src:amylose/acarbose] The combination of acarbose with metformin results in greater reductions of HbA1c, fasting blood glucose and post-prandial glucose than either agent alone.
[src:amylose/acarbose] Since acarbose prevents the degradation of complex carbohydrates into glucose, some carbohydrate will remain in the intestine and be delivered to the colon.
[src:amylose/acarbose] In the colon, bacteria digest (ferment) the complex carbohydrates, causing gastrointestinal side-effects such as flatulence (78% of patients) and diarrhea (14% of patients).
[src:amylose/acarbose] Since these effects are dose-related, in general it is advised to start with a low dose and gradually increase the dose to the desired amount.
[src:amylose/acarbose] One study found that gastrointestinal side effects decreased significantly (from 50% to 15%) over 24 weeks, even on constant dosing.
[src:amylose/acarbose] Sucrose is more likely to trigger GI side effects compared to starch.
[src:amylose/acarbose] Acarbose is associated with very rare elevated transaminases (19 out of 500,000).
[src:amylose/acarbose] Even rarer cases of hepatitis has been reported with acarbose use.
[src:amylose/acarbose] It usually goes away when the medicine is stopped.
[src:amylose/acarbose] Liver enzymes should be checked before and during use of this medicine as a precaution.
[src:amylose/acarbose] A 2016 meta-analysis confirms that alpha-glucosidase inhibitors, including acarbose, have a statistically significant link to elevated transaminase levels.
[src:amylose/acarbose] Acarbose inhibits enzymes (glycoside hydrolases) needed to digest carbohydrates, specifically, alpha-glucosidase enzymes in the brush border of the small intestines, and pancreatic alpha-amylase.
[src:amylose/acarbose] It locks up the enzymes by mimicking the transition state of the substrate with its amine linkage.
[src:amylose/acarbose] However, bacterial alpha-amylases from gut microbiome are able to degrade acarbose.
[src:amylose/acarbose] Pancreatic alpha-amylase hydrolyzes complex starches to oligosaccharides in the lumen of the small intestine, whereas the membrane-bound intestinal alpha-glucosidases hydrolyze oligosaccharides, trisaccharides, and disaccharides to glucose and other monosaccharides in the small intestine.
[src:amylose/acarbose] Inhibition of these enzyme systems reduces the rate of digestion of complex carbohydrates.
[src:amylose/acarbose] Less glucose is absorbed because the carbohydrates are not broken down into glucose molecules.
[src:amylose/acarbose] In diabetic patients, the short-term effect of these drug therapies is to decrease current blood glucose levels; the long-term effect is a reduction in HbA1c level.
[src:amylose/acarbose] Acarbose degradation is the unique feature of glycoside hydrolases in gut microbiota, acarbose degrading glucosidase, which hydrolyze acarbose into an acarviosine-glucose and glucose.
[src:amylose/acarbose] Human enzymes do transform acarbose: the pancreatic alpha-amylase is able to perform a rearrangement reaction, moving the glucose unit in the "tail" maltose to the "head" of the molecule.
[src:amylose/acarbose] Analog drugs with the "tail" glucose removed or flipped to an α(1-6) linkage resist this transformation.
[src:amylose/acarbose] It has been reported that the maltogenic alpha-amylase from *Thermus* sp.
[src:amylose/acarbose] IM6501 (ThMA) and a cyclodextrinase (CDase) from *Streptococcus pyogenes* could hydrolyse acarbose to glucose and acarviosine-glucose, ThMA can further hydrolyze acarviosine-glucose into acarviosin and glucose.
[src:amylose/acarbose] A cyclomaltodextrinase (CDase) from gut bacteria *Lactobacillus plantarum* degraded acarbose via two different modes of action to produce maltose and acarviosin, as well as glucose and acarviosine-glucose, suggest that acarbose resistance is caused by the human microbiome.
[src:amylose/acarbose] The microbiome-derived acarbose kinases are also specific to phosphorylate and inactivate acarbose.
[src:amylose/acarbose] The molecular modeling showed the interaction between gut bacterial acarbose degrading glucosidase and human α-amylase.
[src:amylose/acarbose] In nature, acarbose is synthesized by soil bacteria *Actinoplanes sp* through its precursor valienamine.
[src:amylose/acarbose] Acarbose is described chemically as a pseudotetrasaccharide, specifically a maltotetraose mimic inhibitor.
[src:amylose/acarbose] As an inhibitor that mimics some natural substrates, it is useful for elucidating the structure of sugar-digesting enzymes, by binding into the same pocket.
[src:amylose/acarbose] Most studies investigating alpha-glucosidase and alpha-amylase inhibitory activity use acarbose as reference.
[src:amylose/acarbose] In human T2DM patients, acarbose reduces total triglyceride levels.
[src:amylose/acarbose] Acarbose has a similar effect in non-T2DM patients with isolated familial hypertriglyceridemia.
[src:amylose/acarbose] In smaller samples of healthy human volunteers, acarbose increases postprandial GLP-1 levels.
[src:amylose/acarbose] In studies conducted by three independent laboratories by the US National Institute on Aging's intervention testing programme, acarbose was shown to extend the lifespan of female mice by 5% and of male mice by 22%.
[src:amylose/acarbose] A pooled analysis of data from 10 observational studies show that acarbose appears to reduce body weight irrespective of glycemic control in diabetic patients.
[src:amylose/acarbose] The effect is more pronounced in patients of the female sex, South East Asian and East Asian ethnicity, younger age, higher body mass index, short duration of diabetes, or no previous treatment.
[src:amylose/advances-in-nutrition] Abrams, MD (Dell Medical School at the University of Texas at Austin).
[src:amylose/advances-in-nutrition] According to the *Journal Citation Reports*, the journal has a 2025 impact factor of 9.2.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] In chemistry, a **hexose** is a monosaccharide (simple sugar) with six carbon atoms.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] The chemical formula for all hexoses is C6H12O6, and their molecular weight is 180.156 g/mol.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] Hexoses exist in two forms, open-chain or cyclic, that easily convert into each other in aqueous solutions.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] The open-chain form of a hexose, which usually is favored in solutions, has the general structure H−(CHOH)*n*−1−C(=O)−(CHOH)6−*n*−H, where *n* is 1, 2, 3, 4, 5.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] Namely, five of the carbons have one hydroxyl functional group (−OH) each, connected by a single bond, and one has an oxo group (=O), forming a carbonyl group (C=O).
[src:amylose/aldohexose] The remaining bonds of the carbon atoms are satisfied by seven hydrogen atoms.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] The carbons are commonly numbered 1 to 6 starting at the end closest to the carbonyl.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] Hexoses are extremely important in biochemistry, both as isolated molecules (such as glucose and fructose) and as building blocks of other compounds such as starch, cellulose, and glycosides.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] Hexoses can form dihexose (like sucrose) by a condensation reaction that makes 1,6-glycosidic bond.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] When the carbonyl is in position 1, forming a formyl group (−CH=O), the sugar is called an **aldohexose**, a special case of aldose.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] Otherwise, if the carbonyl position is 2 or 3, the sugar is a derivative of a ketone, and is called a **ketohexose**, a special case of ketose; specifically, an ***n*-ketohexose**.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] However, the 3-ketohexoses have not been observed in nature, and are difficult to synthesize; so the term "ketohexose" usually means 2-ketohexose.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] In the linear form, there are 16 aldohexoses and eight 2-ketohexoses, stereoisomers that differ in the spatial position of the hydroxyl groups.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] These species occur in pairs of optical isomers.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] Each pair has a conventional name (like "glucose" or "fructose"), and the two members are labeled "D-" or "L-", depending on whether the hydroxyl in position 5, in the Fischer projection of the molecule, is to the right or to the left of the axis, respectively.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] These labels are independent of the optical activity of the isomers.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] In general, only one of the two enantiomers occurs naturally (for example, D-glucose) and can be metabolized by animals or fermented by yeasts.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] The term "hexose" sometimes is assumed to include **deoxyhexoses**, such as fucose and rhamnose: compounds with general formula C6H12O6−*y* that can be described as derived from hexoses by replacement of one or more hydroxyl groups with hydrogen atoms.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] The aldohexoses are a subclass of the hexoses which, in the linear form, have the carbonyl at carbon 1, forming an aldehyde derivative with structure H−C(=O)−(CHOH)5−H.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] In linear form, an aldohexose has four chiral centres, which give 16 possible aldohexose stereoisomers (24), comprising 8 pairs of enantiomers.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] Of these D-isomers, all except D-altrose occur in living organisms, but only three are common: D-glucose, D-galactose, and D-mannose.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] The L-isomers are generally absent in living organisms; however, L-altrose has been isolated from strains of the bacterium *Butyrivibrio fibrisolvens*.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] When drawn in this order, the Fischer projections of the D-aldohexoses can be identified with the 3-digit binary numbers from 0 to 7, namely 000, 001, 010, 011, 100, 101, 110, 111.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] The three bits, from left to right, indicate the position of the hydroxyls on carbons 4, 3, and 2, respectively: to the right if the bit value is 0, and to the left if the value is 1.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] The Fischer diagrams of the eight L-aldohexoses are the mirror images of the corresponding D-isomers; with all hydroxyls reversed, including the one on carbon 5.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] A ketohexose is a ketone-containing hexose.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] The important ketohexoses are the 2-ketohexoses, and the most important 2-ketose is fructose.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] Besides the 2-ketoses, there are only the 3-Ketoses, and they do not exist in nature, although at least one 3-ketohexose has been synthesized, with great difficulty.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] In the linear form, the 2-ketohexoses have three chiral centers and therefore eight possible stereoisomers (23), comprising four pairs of enantiomers.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] The corresponding L forms have the hydroxyls on carbons 3, 4, and 5 reversed.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] In theory, the ketohexoses include also the 3-ketohexoses, which have the carbonyl in position 3; namely H−(CHOH)2−C(=O)−(CHOH)3−H.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] However, these compounds are not known to occur in nature, and are difficult to synthesize.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] In 1897, an unfermentable product obtained by treatment of fructose with bases, in particular lead(II) hydroxide, was given the name *glutose*, a portmanteau of *glucose* and *fructose*, and was claimed to be a 3-ketohexose.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] However, subsequent studies showed that the substance was a mixture of various other compounds.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] The unequivocal synthesis and isolation of a 3-ketohexose, *xylo*-3-hexulose, through a rather complex route, was first reported in 1961 by George U.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] Like most monosaccharides with five or more carbons, each aldohexose or 2-ketohexose also exists in one or more cyclic (closed-chain) forms, derived from the open-chain form by an internal rearrangement between the carbonyl group and one of the hydroxyl groups.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] The reaction turns the =O group into a hydroxyl, and the hydroxyl into an ether bridge (−O−) between the two carbon atoms, thus creating a ring with one oxygen atom and four or five carbons.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] If the cycle has five carbon atoms (six atoms in total), the closed form is called a pyranose, after the cyclic ether tetrahydropyran, that has the same ring.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] If the cycle has four carbon atoms (five in total), the form is called furanose after the compound tetrahydrofuran.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] The conventional numbering of the carbons in the closed form is the same as in the open-chain form.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] If the sugar is an aldohexose, with the carbonyl in position 1, the reaction may involve the hydroxyl on carbon 4 or carbon 5, creating a hemiacetal with five- or six-membered ring, respectively.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] If the sugar is a 2-ketohexose, it can only involve the hydroxyl in carbon 5, and will create a hemiketal with a five-membered ring.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] The closure turns the carboxyl carbon into a chiral center, which may have either of two configurations, depending on the position of the new hydroxyl.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] Therefore, each hexose in linear form can produce two distinct closed forms, identified by prefixes "α" and "β".
[src:amylose/aldohexose] It has been known since 1926 that hexoses in the crystalline solid state assume the cyclic form.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] The "α" and "β" forms, which are not enantiomers, will usually crystallize separately as distinct species.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] For example, D-glucose forms an α crystal that has specific rotation of +112° and melting point of 146 °C, as well as a β crystal that has specific rotation of +19° and melting point of 150 °C.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] The linear form does not crystallize, and exists only in small amounts in water solutions, where it is in equilibrium with the closed forms.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] Nevertheless, it plays an essential role as the intermediate stage between those closed forms.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] In particular, the "α" and "β" forms can convert to into each other by returning to the open-chain form and then closing in the opposite configuration.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] Although all hexoses have similar structures and share some general properties, each enantiomer pair has its own chemistry.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] Fructose is soluble in water, alcohol, and ether.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] The two enantiomers of each pair generally have vastly different biological properties.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] 2-Ketohexoses are stable over a wide pH range, and with a primary p*K*a of 10.28, will only deprotonate at high pH, so are marginally less stable than aldohexoses in solution.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] The aldohexose that is most important in biochemistry is D-glucose, which is the main "fuel" for metabolism in many living organisms.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] The 2-ketohexoses psicose, fructose and tagatose occur naturally as the D-isomers, whereas sorbose occurs naturally as the L-isomer.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] D-Sorbose is commonly used in the commercial synthesis of ascorbic acid.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] D-Tagatose is a rare natural ketohexose that is found in small quantities in food.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] D-Fructose is responsible for the sweet taste of many fruits, and is a building block of sucrose, the common sugar.
[src:amylose/aldohexose] The term "hexose" may sometimes be used to include the deoxyhexoses, which have one or more hydroxyls (−OH) replaced by hydrogen atoms (−H).
[src:amylose/aldohexose] It is named as the parent hexose, with the prefix "*x*-deoxy-", the *x* indicating the carbon with the affected hydroxyl.
[src:amylose/aldose] An **aldose** is a monosaccharide (a simple sugar) with a carbon backbone chain with a carbonyl group on the endmost carbon atom, making it an aldehyde, and hydroxyl groups connected to all the other carbon atoms.
[src:amylose/aldose] Aldoses can be distinguished from ketoses, which have the carbonyl group away from the end of the molecule, and are therefore ketones.
[src:amylose/aldose] Like most carbohydrates, simple aldoses have the general chemical formula C*n*(H2O)*n*.
[src:amylose/aldose] Because formaldehyde (n=1) and glycolaldehyde (n=2) are not generally considered to be carbohydrates, the simplest possible aldose is the triose glyceraldehyde, which only contains three carbon atoms.
[src:amylose/aldose] Because they have at least one asymmetric carbon center, all aldoses exhibit stereoisomerism.
[src:amylose/aldose] Aldoses can exist in either a D- form or L- form.
[src:amylose/aldose] The determination is made based on the chirality of the asymmetric carbon furthest from the aldehyde end, namely the second-last carbon in the chain.
[src:amylose/aldose] Aldoses with alcohol groups on the right of the Fischer projection are D-aldoses, and those with alcohols on the left are L-aldoses.
[src:amylose/aldose] D-aldoses are more common than L-aldoses in nature.
[src:amylose/aldose] Examples of aldoses include glyceraldehyde, erythrose, ribose, glucose and galactose.
[src:amylose/aldose] Ketoses and aldoses can be chemically differentiated through Seliwanoff's test, where the sample is heated with acid and resorcinol.
[src:amylose/aldose] The test relies on the dehydration reaction which occurs more quickly in ketoses, so that while aldoses react slowly, producing a light pink color, ketoses react more quickly and strongly to produce a dark red color.
[src:amylose/aldose] Aldoses can isomerize to ketoses through the Lobry-de Bruyn-van Ekenstein transformation.
[src:amylose/aldose] Aldoses are differentiated by the number of carbon atoms in the main chain.
[src:amylose/aldose] The minimum number of carbon atoms in a backbone needed to form a molecule that is still considered a carbohydrate is 3, and carbohydrates with three carbon atoms are called trioses.
[src:amylose/aldose] The only aldotriose is glyceraldehyde, which has one chiral stereocenter with 2 possible enantiomers, D- and L-glyceraldehyde.
[src:amylose/aldose] The most commonly discussed category of aldoses are those with six carbon atoms, aldohexoses.
[src:amylose/aldose] Aldoses are commonly referred to by names specific to one stereoisomer of the compound.
[src:amylose/aldose] This distinction is especially vital in biochemistry, as many systems can only use one enantiomer of the carbohydrate and not the other.
[src:amylose/aldose] However, aldoses are not locked into any one conformation: they can and do fluctuate between different forms.
[src:amylose/aldose] Aldoses can tautomerize to ketoses in a dynamic process with an enol intermediate (more specifically, an enediol).
[src:amylose/aldose] This process is reversible, so aldoses and ketoses can be thought of as being in equilibrium with each other.
[src:amylose/aldose] However, aldehydes and ketones are almost always more stable than the corresponding enol forms, so the aldo- and keto- forms normally predominate.
[src:amylose/aldose] This process, with its enol intermediate, also allows stereoisomerization.
[src:amylose/aldose] Basic solutions accelerate the interconversion of isomers.
[src:amylose/aldose] Carbohydrates with more than four carbon atoms exist in an equilibrium between the closed ring, or cyclic form, and the open-chain form.
[src:amylose/aldose] Cyclic aldoses are usually drawn as Haworth projections, and open chain forms are commonly drawn as Fischer projections, both of which represent important stereochemical information about the forms they depict.
[src:amylose/alginate] It is a significant component of the biofilms produced by the bacterium *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*, a major pathogen found in the lungs of some people who have cystic fibrosis.
[src:amylose/alginate] The biofilm and *P. aeruginosa* have a high resistance to antibiotics, but are susceptible to inhibition by macrophages.
[src:amylose/alginate] Alginate was discovered by the British chemical scientist E.
[src:amylose/alginate] Stanford in 1881, and he patented an extraction process for it in the same year.
[src:amylose/alginate] The alginate was extracted, in the original patent, by first soaking the algae in water or diluted acid.
[src:amylose/alginate] The resulting insoluble alginic acid is then treated with an alkaline solution such as sodium carbonate, creating sodium alginate, before finally precipitating and purifying the alginate from solution.
[src:amylose/alginate] Alginic acid is a linear copolymer with homopolymeric blocks of (1→4)-linked β-D-mannuronate (M) and α-L-guluronate (G) residues, respectively, covalently linked together in different sequences or blocks.
[src:amylose/alginate] The monomers may appear in homopolymeric blocks of consecutive G-residues (G-blocks), consecutive M-residues (M-blocks) or alternating M and G-residues (MG-blocks). α-L-guluronate is the C-5 epimer of β-D-mannuronate.
[src:amylose/alginate] Alginates are refined from brown seaweeds.
[src:amylose/alginate] Throughout the world, many of the Phaeophyceae class brown seaweeds are harvested to be processed and converted into sodium alginate.
[src:amylose/alginate] Sodium alginate is used in many industries including food, animal food, fertilisers, textile printing, and pharmaceuticals.
[src:amylose/alginate] Dental impression material uses alginate as its means of gelling.
[src:amylose/alginate] Food grade alginate is an approved ingredient in processed and manufactured foods.
[src:amylose/alginate] Brown seaweeds range in size from the giant kelp *Macrocystis pyrifera* which can be 20–40 meters long, to thick, leather-like seaweeds from 2–4 m long, to smaller species 30–60 cm long.
[src:amylose/alginate] Most brown seaweed used for alginates are gathered from the wild, with the exception of *Laminaria japonica*, which is cultivated in China for food and its surplus material is diverted to the alginate industry in China.
[src:amylose/alginate] Alginates from different species of brown seaweed vary in their chemical structure, resulting in different physical properties of alginates.
[src:amylose/alginate] Some species yield an alginate that gives a strong gel, another a weaker gel, some may produce a cream or white alginate, while others are difficult to gel and are best used for technical applications where color does not matter.
[src:amylose/alginate] Commercial grade alginate is extracted from giant kelp *Macrocystis pyrifera*, *Ascophyllum nodosum*, and types of *Laminaria*.
[src:amylose/alginate] Alginates are also produced by two bacterial genera *Pseudomonas* and *Azotobacter*, which played a major role in the unravelling of its biosynthesis pathway.
[src:amylose/alginate] Bacterial alginates are useful for the production of micro- or nanostructures suitable for medical applications.
[src:amylose/alginate] Sodium alginate (NaC6H7O6) is the sodium salt of alginic acid.
[src:amylose/alginate] Potassium alginate (KC6H7O6) is the potassium salt of alginic acid.
[src:amylose/alginate] Calcium alginate (CaC12H14O12) is the calcium salt of alginic acid.
[src:amylose/alginate] It is made by replacing the sodium ion in sodium alginate with a calcium ion (ion exchange).
[src:amylose/alginate] Chemically the process is simple, but difficulties arise from the physical separations required between the slimy residues from viscous solutions and the separation of gelatinous precipitates that hold large amounts of liquid within their structure, so they resist filtration and centrifugation.
[src:amylose/alginate] The conventional process involves large amounts of reagents and solvents, as well as time-consuming steps.
[src:amylose/alginate] Simpler and newer techniques, such as microwave-assisted extraction, ultrasound, high pressure, pressurized fluid extraction, and enzyme-assisted extraction, are the subject of research.
[src:amylose/alginate] The most common, conventional extraction process involves six steps: pre-treatment of the algal biomass, acid treatment, alkaline extraction, precipitation, bleaching, and drying.
[src:amylose/alginate] Pre-treatments mainly aim at either breaking the cell wall to help extract the alginate, or removing other compounds and contaminants from the algae.
[src:amylose/alginate] Drying is of the first kind, also helping to prevent bacterial growth; algae which is dried is also usually powdered to expose more surface area.
[src:amylose/alginate] Common treatments to remove contaminants include treatments with ethanol and formaldehyde, the latter of which is very common; ethanol solutions help remove compounds bonded to the alginate, and formaldehyde solutions help prevent enzymatic or microbial reactions.
[src:amylose/alginate] The algae is then treated with an acidic solution to help disrupt cell walls, which converts the alginate salts into insoluble alginic acid; a subsequently applied alkaline solution (pH 9-10), usually sodium carbonate, converts it back into water-soluble sodium alginate, which is then precipitated.
[src:amylose/alginate] It is also possible to extract the alginate directly with an alkaline treatment, but this is less common.
[src:amylose/alginate] Alginic acid is usually precipitated, through different techniques, with either an alcohol (usually ethanol), calcium chloride, or hydrochloric acid.
[src:amylose/alginate] After the alginin is precipitated into a fine paste, it is dried, ground to the desired grain size, and finally purified through a variety of techniques.
[src:amylose/alginate] Commercial alginate for biomedical and pharmaceutical use is extracted and purified through more rigorous techniques, but these are trade secrets.
[src:amylose/alginate] Various alginate-based materials can be produced, including porous scaffold material, alginate hydrogel, nonwoven fabric, and alginate membranes.
[src:amylose/alginate] Techniques used to produce these include ion cross-linking, microfluidic spinning, freeze drying, wet spinning, and immersive centrifugal jet spinning.
[src:amylose/alginate] Calcium salts added to a sodium alginate solution to induce ionic cross-linking, which produces the hydrogel.
[src:amylose/alginate] Freeze-drying the hydrogel to eliminate water produces the porous scaffold material.
[src:amylose/alginate] Wet spinning consists of extruding an alginate solution from a spinneret into a calcium salt solution to induce ionic cross-linking (forming the gel), and then drawing the fibers out of the bath with draft rollers.
[src:amylose/alginate] Microfluidic spinning, a simpler and more eco-friendly implementation of the process, involves introducing calcium salt flows flowing alongside and touching a central "core" flow of alginate.
[src:amylose/alginate] The fiber then emerges from the core flow.
[src:amylose/alginate] This technique can be used to produce shaped and grooved fibers.
[src:amylose/alginate] Alginate fiber, which is used in fabric, is usually produced through either microfluidic spinning, wet spinning, or electrospinning to obtain thinner fibers.
[src:amylose/alginate] Those fibers are used to produce alginate nonwoven fabric by carding and needle punching.
[src:amylose/alginate] The resulting felts are used in wound dressings, facial masks, and tissue scaffolds due to its hygroscopic and water retention ability.
[src:amylose/alginate] As of 2022, alginate had become one of the most preferred materials as an abundant natural biopolymer.
[src:amylose/alginate] It is particularly useful as a biomaterial because of its nontoxicity, hygroscopicity, and biocompatibility, and can imitate local bioenvironments; its degradation product can be easily cleared by the kidneys.
[src:amylose/alginate] Alginate absorbs water quickly, which makes it useful as an additive in dehydrated products such as slimming aids, and in the manufacture of paper and textiles.
[src:amylose/alginate] Alginate is also used for waterproofing and fireproofing fabrics, in the food industry as a thickening agent for drinks, ice cream, cosmetics, as a gelling agent for jellies, known by the code E401 and sausage casing.
[src:amylose/alginate] Sodium alginate is mixed with soybean protein to make meat analogue.
[src:amylose/alginate] Alginate is used as an ingredient in various pharmaceutical preparations, such as Gaviscon, in which it combines with bicarbonate to inhibit gastroesophageal reflux.
[src:amylose/alginate] Sodium alginate is used as an impression-making material in dentistry, prosthetics, lifecasting, and for creating positives for small-scale casting.
[src:amylose/alginate] Sodium alginate is used in reactive dye printing and as a thickener for reactive dyes in textile screen-printing.
[src:amylose/alginate] Alginates do not react with these dyes and wash out easily, unlike starch-based thickeners.
[src:amylose/alginate] It also serves as a material for micro-encapsulation.
[src:amylose/alginate] Calcium alginate is used in different types of medical products, including skin wound dressings, in the form of hydrogels, to promote healing, since alginate can increase the fluid uptake capacity of dressings, reducing the amount of times the dressing needs to be changed.
[src:amylose/alginate] In research on bone reconstruction, alginate composites have favorable properties encouraging regeneration, such as improved porosity, cell proliferation, and mechanical strength.
[src:amylose/alginate] Alginate hydrogel is a common biomaterial for bio-fabrication of scaffolds and tissue regeneration.
[src:amylose/alginate] Covalent bonding of thiol groups to alginate improves in-situ gelling and mucoadhesive properties; the thiolated polymer (thiomer) forms disulfide bonds within its polymeric network and with cysteine-rich subdomains of the mucus layer.
[src:amylose/alginate] Thiolated alginates are used as in situ gelling hydrogels, and are under preliminary research as possible mucoadhesive drug delivery systems.
[src:amylose/alginate] Alginate hydrogels may be used for drug delivery, exhibiting responses to pH changes, temperature changes, redox, and the presence of enzymes.
[src:amylose/alginate] Alginate is one of the most widely used polymers in bioencapsulation, particularly for the immobilisation or protection of living cells, enzymes, proteins and other bioactive materials.
[src:amylose/alginate] Its use is largely based on the ability of soluble alginate to form calcium alginate hydrogels under mild aqueous conditions, allowing biological material to be entrapped without exposure to harsh solvents, high temperature or aggressive chemical reactions.
[src:amylose/alginate] In cell encapsulation, alginate beads or microcapsules can provide a semipermeable hydrogel matrix that permits diffusion of nutrients, oxygen and secreted products while physically separating the encapsulated cells from the surrounding environment.
[src:amylose/alginate] This approach has been investigated for immunoisolation, islet transplantation, cell therapy, tissue engineering and controlled delivery of biological products.
[src:amylose/alginate] Alginate bioencapsulation systems can be produced by dripping, extrusion, air-jet cutting, electrostatic droplet generation, emulsification and microfluidic methods.
[src:amylose/alginate] These techniques differ in throughput, bead-size control, size distribution and suitability for encapsulating cells or labile biomolecules.
[src:amylose/allose] Reduction of allose by catalytic hydrogenation produces an obscure sugar alcohol allitol which is rarely used in the chemical industry.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] It is the major form of amylase found in humans and other mammals.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] It is also present in seeds containing starch as a food reserve, and is secreted by many fungi.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] It is a member of glycoside hydrolase family 13.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] Although found in many tissues, amylase is most prominent in pancreatic juice and saliva, each of which has its own isoform of human α-amylase.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] They behave differently on isoelectric focusing, and can also be separated in testing by using specific monoclonal antibodies.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] In humans, all amylase isoforms link to chromosome 1p21 (see AMY1A).
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] Amylase is found in saliva and breaks starch into maltose and dextrin.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] This form of amylase is also called "ptyalin" /ˈtaɪəlɪn/, which was named by chemist Jöns Jacob Berzelius.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] The name derives from the Greek word πτυω (I spit), because the substance was obtained from saliva.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] It will break large, insoluble starch molecules into soluble starches (amylodextrin, erythrodextrin, and achrodextrin) producing successively smaller starches and ultimately maltose.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] Ptyalin acts on linear α(1,4) glycosidic linkages, but compound hydrolysis requires an enzyme that acts on branched products.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] Salivary amylase is inactivated in the stomach by gastric acid.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] In gastric juice adjusted to pH 3.3, ptyalin was totally inactivated in 20 minutes at 37 °C.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] In contrast, 50% of amylase activity remained after 150 minutes of exposure to gastric juice at pH 4.3.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] Both starch, the substrate for ptyalin, and the product (short chains of glucose) are able to partially protect it against inactivation by gastric acid.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] Ptyalin added to buffer at pH 3.0 underwent complete inactivation in 120 minutes; however, addition of starch at a 0.1% level resulted in 10% of the activity remaining, and similar addition of starch to a 1.0% level resulted in about 40% of the activity remaining at 120 minutes.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] The salivary amylase gene has undergone duplication during evolution, and DNA hybridization studies indicate many individuals have multiple tandem repeats of the gene.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] The number of gene copies correlates with the levels of salivary amylase, as measured by protein blot assays using antibodies to human amylase.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] Gene copy number is associated with apparent evolutionary exposure to high-starch diets.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] For example, a Japanese individual had 14 copies of the amylase gene (one allele with 10 copies, and a second allele with four copies).
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] The Japanese diet has traditionally contained large amounts of rice starch.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] In contrast, a Biaka individual carried six copies (three copies on each allele).
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] The Biaka are rainforest hunter-gatherers who have traditionally consumed a low-starch diet.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] Perry and colleagues speculated the increased copy number of the salivary amylase gene may have enhanced survival coincident to a shift to a starchy diet during human evolution.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] Pancreatic α-amylase randomly cleaves the α(1-4) glycosidic linkages of amylose to yield dextrin, maltose, or maltotriose.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] It adopts a double displacement mechanism with retention of anomeric configuration.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] In humans, the salivary amylase evolved from a copy of it.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] The test for amylase is easier to perform than that for lipase, making it the primary test used to detect and monitor pancreatitis.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] Medical laboratories will usually measure either pancreatic amylase or total amylase.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] If only pancreatic amylase is measured, an increase will not be noted with mumps or other salivary gland trauma.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] However, because of the small amount present, timing is critical when sampling blood for this measurement.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] Blood should be taken soon after a bout of pancreatitis pain, otherwise it is excreted rapidly by the kidneys.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] Salivary α-amylase has been used as a biomarker for stress and as a surrogate marker of sympathetic nervous system (SNS) activity that does not require a blood draw.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] Total amylase readings of over 10 times the upper limit of normal (ULN) are suggestive of pancreatitis.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] Five to 10 times the ULN may indicate ileus or duodenal disease or kidney failure, and lower elevations are commonly found in salivary gland disease.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] α-Amylase activity in grain is measured by, for instance, the Hagberg–Perten Falling Number, a test to assess sprout damages, or the Phadebas method.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] α-Amylase is used in ethanol production to break starches in grains into fermentable sugars.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] The first step in the production of high-fructose corn syrup is the treatment of cornstarch with α-amylase, which cleaves the long starch polymers into shorter chains of oligosaccharides.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] An α-amylase called "Termamyl", sourced from *Bacillus licheniformis*, is also used in some detergents, especially dishwashing and starch-removing detergents.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] See amylase for more uses of the amylase family in general.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] α-Amylase has exhibited efficacy in degrading polymicrobial bacterial biofilms by hydrolyzing the α(1→4) glycosidic linkages within the structural, matrix exopolysaccharides of the extracellular polymeric substance (EPS).
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] The tris molecule is reported to inhibit a number of bacterial α-amylases, so they should not be used in tris buffer.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] Several methods are available for determination of α-amylase activity, and different industries tend to rely on different methods.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] The starch iodine test, a development of the iodine test, is based on colour change, as α-amylase degrades starch and is commonly used in many applications.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] A similar but industrially produced test is the Phadebas amylase test, which is used as a qualitative and quantitative test within many industries, such as detergents, various flour, grain, and malt foods, and forensic biology.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] Modified colorimetric microdetermination of amylase is described in which the digestion of starch is measured by the decrease in the starch-iodine color.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] α-Amylases contain a number of distinct protein domains.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] The catalytic domain has a structure consisting of an eight-stranded α/β barrel that contains the active site, interrupted by a ~70-amino acid calcium-binding domain protruding between β-strand 3 and α-helix 3, and a carboxyl-terminal Greek key β-barrel domain.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] Several α-amylases contain a β-sheet domain, usually at the C terminus.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] This domain is organised as a five-stranded antiparallel β-sheet.
[src:amylose/alpha-amylase] Several α-amylases contain an all-β domain, usually at the C terminus.
[src:amylose/amylose] Amylose is made up of α(1→4) bound glucose molecules.
[src:amylose/amylose] The carbon atoms on glucose are numbered, starting at the aldehyde (C=O) carbon, so, in amylose, the 1-carbon on one glucose molecule is linked to the 4-carbon on the next glucose molecule (α(1→4) bonds).
[src:amylose/amylose] The structural formula of amylose is pictured at right.
[src:amylose/amylose] The number of repeated glucose subunits (n) is usually in the range of 300 to 3000, but can be many thousands.
[src:amylose/amylose] There are three main forms of amylose chains can take.
[src:amylose/amylose] It can exist in a disordered amorphous conformation, found both in starch granules and in hydrated amylose (when starch is cooked in water).
[src:amylose/amylose] There are also two different helical forms.
[src:amylose/amylose] Starting with purified amylose, it can bind with another amylose molecule in a double helix (A or B form), or it can bind with a guest molecule such as iodine, a fatty acid, or an aromatic compound, known as the V form.
[src:amylose/amylose] Within this form, there are many different variations.
[src:amylose/amylose] Each is notated with V and then a subscript indicating the number of glucose units per turn.
[src:amylose/amylose] The most common is the V6 form, which has six glucose units a turn.
[src:amylose/amylose] These provide an even larger space for the guest molecule to bind.
[src:amylose/amylose] This linear structure can have some rotation around the phi and psi angles, but for the most part bound glucose ring oxygens lie on one side of the structure.
[src:amylose/amylose] The α(1→4) structure promotes the formation of a helix structure, making it possible for hydrogen bonds to form between the oxygen atoms bound at the 2-carbon of one glucose molecule and the 3-carbon of the next glucose molecule.
[src:amylose/amylose] Fiber X-ray diffraction analysis coupled with computer-based structure refinement has found A-, B-, and C- polymorphs of amylose.
[src:amylose/amylose] Each form corresponds to either the A-, the B-, or the C- starch forms.
[src:amylose/amylose] A- and B- structures have different helical crystal structures and water contents, whereas the C- structure is a mixture of A- and B- unit cells, resulting in an intermediate packing density between the two forms.
[src:amylose/amylose] High-amylose forms of starch make it more resistant to digestion.
[src:amylose/amylose] It also reduces the crystallinity of amylopectin and how easily water can infiltrate the starch.
[src:amylose/amylose] The higher the amylose content, the less expansion potential and the lower the gel strength for the same starch concentration.
[src:amylose/amylose] This can be countered partially by increasing the granule size.
[src:amylose/amylose] Amylose is important in plant energy storage.
[src:amylose/amylose] It is less readily digested than amylopectin.
[src:amylose/amylose] It makes up about 30% of the stored starch in plants, though the percentage varies by species and variety.
[src:amylose/amylose] The digestive enzyme α-amylase breaks down starch molecules into maltotriose and maltose, which can be used as sources of energy.
[src:amylose/amylose] Amylose is also an important thickener, water binder, emulsion stabilizer, and gelling agent in industrial and food-based contexts.
[src:amylose/amylose] Loose helical amylose chains have a hydrophobic interior that can bind to hydrophobic molecules such as lipids and aromatic compounds.
[src:amylose/amylose] The one problem with this is that, when it crystallizes or associates, it can lose some stability, often releasing water in the process (syneresis).
[src:amylose/amylose] When amylose concentration is increased, gel stickiness decreases but firmness increases.
[src:amylose/amylose] When other things, including amylopectin, bind to amylose, the viscosity can be affected, but incorporating κ-carrageenan, alginate, xanthan gum, or low-molecular-weight sugars can reduce the loss in stability.
[src:amylose/amylose] The ability to bind water can add substance to food, possibly serving as a fat replacement.
[src:amylose/amylose] For example, amylose is responsible for causing white sauce to thicken, but, upon cooling, the solid and the water will partly separate.
[src:amylose/amylose] Amylose is known for its good film-forming properties, useful in food packaging.
[src:amylose/amylose] Excellent film-forming behavior of amylose was studied already in 1950s.
[src:amylose/amylose] Amylose films are better for both barrier properties and mechanical properties when compared to the amylopectin films.
[src:amylose/amylose] In a laboratory setting, it can act as a marker.
[src:amylose/amylose] Iodine molecules fit neatly inside the helical structure of amylose, binding with the starch polymer that absorbs certain known wavelengths of light.
[src:amylose/amylose] Hence, a common test is the iodine test for starch.
[src:amylose/amylose] If starch is mixed with a small amount of yellow iodine solution, a blue-black color will be observed.
[src:amylose/amylose] The intensity of the color can be tested with a colorimeter, using a red filter to discern the concentration of starch present in the solution.
[src:amylose/amylose] It is also possible to use starch as an indicator in titrations involving iodine reduction.
[src:amylose/amylose] It is also used in amylose magnetic beads and resin to separate maltose-binding protein.
[src:amylose/amylose] High-amylose varieties of rice, the less sticky long-grain rice, have a much lower glycemic load, which could be beneficial for diabetics.
[src:amylose/amylose] Researchers have identified the Granule Bound Starch Synthase (GBSS) as the enzyme that specifically elongates amylose during starch biosynthesis in plants.
[src:amylose/amylose] The waxy locus in maize encodes for the GBSS protein.
[src:amylose/amylose] Mutants lacking the GBSS protein produce starch containing only amylopectin, such as in waxy corn.
[src:amylose/amylose] In Arabidopsis leaves, another gene, encoding the Protein Targeting to STarch (PTST) protein, is required in addition to GBSS for amylose synthesis.
[src:amylose/amylose] Mutants lacking either protein produce starch without amylose.
[src:amylose/amylose] Genetically modified potato cultivar Amflora by BASF Plant Science was developed to not produce amylose.
